SIMPLE: post
RECORDS: 7

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Post-
<hw>Post-</hw> <pr>(p⟦omac⟧st)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>post</ets> behind,
after; cf. Skr. <ets>pa⟦cced⟧c⟦amac⟧</ets>behind, afterwards.]</ety>
<def>A prefix signifying <xex>behind</xex>, <xex>back</xex>,
<xex>after</xex>; <as>as, <ex>post</ex>commissure, <ex>post</ex>dot,
<ex>post</ex>script</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>aposter</ets> to place in a
post or position, generally for a bad purpose.]</ety> <def>Hired to do
what is wrong; suborned.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir E.
Sandys.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS., fr. L. <ets>postis</ets>, akin
to <ets>ponere</ets>, <ets>positum</ets>, to place. See
<er>Position</er>, and cf. 4th <er>Post</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
piece of timber, metal, or other solid substance, fixed, or to be fixed,
firmly in an upright position, especially when intended as a stay or
support to something else; a pillar; <as>as, a hitching <ex>post</ex>; a
fence <ex>post</ex>; the <ex>posts</ex> of a house.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They shall take of the blood, and strike it on the two side
<qex>posts</qex> and on the upper doorpost of the houses.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then by main force pulled up, and on his shoulders bore,⟦br⟧
The gates of Azza, <qex>post</qex> and massy bar.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unto his order he was a noble <qex>post</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Post</xex>, in the sense of an upright timber or
strut, is used in composition, in such words as king-<xex>post</xex>,
queen-<xex>post</xex>, crown-<xex>post</xex>, gate<xex>post</xex>,
etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The doorpost of a victualer's shop or inn, on which
were chalked the scores of customers; hence, a score; a debt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When God sends coin⟦br⟧
I will discharge your <qex>post</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>S.
Rowlands.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>From pillar to post</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Pillar</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Knight of the post</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Knight</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Post hanger</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a bearing for a revolving shaft, adapted to be
fastened to a post.</cd> -- <col><b>Post hole</b></col>, <cd>a hole in
the ground to set the foot of a post in.</cd> -- <col><b>Post
mill</b></col>, <cd>a form of windmill so constructed that the whole
fabric rests on a vertical axis firmly fastened to the ground, and
capable of being turned as the direction of the wind varies.</cd> --
<col><b>Post and stall</b></col> <fld>(Coal Mining)</fld>, <cd>a mode of
working in which pillars of coal are left to support the roof of the
mine.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>poste</ets>, LL.
<ets>posta</ets> station, post (where horses were kept), properly, a
fixed or set place, fem. fr. L. <ets>positus</ets> placed, p. p. of
<ets>ponere</ets>. See <er>Position</er>, and cf. <er>Post</er> a
pillar.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The place at which anything is stopped,
placed, or fixed; a station.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A
station, or one of a series of stations, established for the refreshment
and accommodation of travelers on some recognized route; <as>as, a stage
or railway <ex>post</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A military
station; the place at which a soldier or a body of troops is stationed;
also, the troops at such a station.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The piece of
ground to which a sentinel's walk is limited.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A messenger who goes from station; an express;
especially, one who is employed by the government to carry letters and
parcels regularly from one place to another; a letter carrier; a
postman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In certain places there be always fresh <qex>posts</qex>, to carry
that further which is brought unto them by the other.</q> <rj><qau>Abp.
Abbot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fear my Julia would not deign my lines,⟦br⟧
Receiving them from such a worthless <qex>post</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An established conveyance for letters from one place
or station to another; especially, the governmental system in any
country for carrying and distributing letters and parcels; the post
office; the mail; hence, the carriage by which the mail is
transported.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I send you the fair copy of the poem on dullness, which I should
not care to hazard by the common <qex>post</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Haste or speed, like that of a messenger or mail
carrier.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>post</xex> he
came.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who has charge of a station, especially of a
postal station.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He held office of postmaster, or, as it was then called,
<qex>post</qex>, for several years.</q> <rj><qau>Palfrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A station, office, or position of service, trust, or
emolument; <as>as, the <ex>post</ex> of duty; the <ex>post</ex> of
danger.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>post</qex> of honor is a private station.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A size of printing and writing paper. See the Table
under <er>Paper</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Post and pair</b></col>, <cd>an old game at cards, in
which each player a hand of three cards.</cd> <au>B. Jonson.</au> --
<col><b>Post bag</b></col>, <cd>a mail bag.</cd> -- <col><b>Post
bill</b></col>, <cd>a bill of letters mailed by a postmaster.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Post chaise</b></col>, or <col><b>Post
coach</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a carriage usually with four wheels, for the
conveyance of travelers who travel post.</cd> -- <col><b>Post
day</b></col>, <cd>a day on which the mall arrives or departs.</cd> --
<col><b>Post hackney</b></col>, <cd>a hired post horse.</cd> <au>Sir H.
Wotton.</au> -- <col><b>Post horn</b></col>, <cd>a horn, or trumpet,
carried and blown by a carrier of the public mail, or by a
coachman.</cd> -- <col><b>Post horse</b></col>, <cd>a horse stationed,
intended, or used for the post.</cd> -- <col><b>Post hour</b></col>,
<cd>hour for posting letters.</cd> <au>Dickens.</au> -- <col><b>Post
office</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>An office under governmental
superintendence, where letters, papers, and other mailable matter, are
received and distributed; a place appointed for attending to all
business connected with the mail</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The governmental
system for forwarding mail matter.</cd> -- <col><b>Postoffice
order</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Money order</cref>, under
<er>Money</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Post road</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Post route</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a road or way over which the
mail is carried.</cd> -- <col><b>Post town</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
town in which post horses are kept</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A town in
which a post office is established by law.</cd> -- <col><b>To ride
post</b></col>, <cd>to ride, as a carrier of dispatches, from place to
place; hence, to ride rapidly, with as little delay as possible.</cd> --
<col><b>To travel post</b></col>, <cd>to travel, as a post does, by
relays of horses, or by keeping one carriage to which fresh horses are
attached at each stopping place.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Posted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Posting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To attach to a post,
a wall, or other usual place of affixing public notices; to placard;
<as>as, to <ex>post</ex> a notice; to <ex>post</ex>
playbills.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Formerly, a large post was erected before the sheriff's
office, or in some public place, upon which legal notices were
displayed. This way of advertisement has not entirely gone of
use.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hold up to public blame or reproach; to advertise
opprobriously; to denounce by public proclamation; <as>as, to
<ex>post</ex> one for cowardice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On pain of being <qex>posted</qex> to your sorrow⟦br⟧
Fail not, at four, to meet me.</q> <rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To enter (a name) on a list, as for service,
promotion, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To assign to a station; to set; to place; <as>as, to
<ex>post</ex> a sentinel</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧It might be to obtain a ship
for a lieutenant, . . . or to get him <xex>posted</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bookkeeping)</fld> <def>To carry, as an account,
from the journal to the ledger; <as>as, to <ex>post</ex> an
account</as>; to transfer, as accounts, to the ledger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have not <qex>posted</qex> your books these ten years.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To place in the care of the post; to mail; <as>as,
to <ex>post</ex> a letter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To inform; to give the news to; to make (one)
acquainted with the details of a subject; -- often with
<xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thoroughly <qex>posted</qex> up in the politics and literature of
the day.</q> <rj><qau>Lond. Sat. Rev.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To post off</b></col>, <cd>to put off; to delay.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Why did I, venturously, <xex>post off</xex>
so great a business?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Baxter.</au> -- <col><b>To post
over</b></col>, <cd>to hurry over.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>Fuller.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>poster</ets>. See 4th
<er>Post</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To travel with post horses;
figuratively, to travel in haste.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Post</xex> seedily
to my lord your husband.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>post</qex> o'er land and ocean without rest.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Man.)</fld> <def>To rise and sink in the saddle, in
accordance with the motion of the horse, esp. in trotting.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Post
<hw>Post</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With post horses; hence, in haste;
<as>as, to travel <ex>post</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Post-abdomen</ent>⟦br⟧
